- The **Battle of Koregaon**  (also called the Battle of Koregaon Bhima) was fought on 1 January 1818 between the [British East India Company](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_East_India_Company)  and the [Peshwa](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peshwa)  faction of the [Maratha Confederacy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maratha_Confederacy) , at [Koregaon Bhima](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koregaon_Bhima) .
    - A 28,000-strong force led by Peshwa [Baji Rao II](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baji_Rao_II) whilst on their way to attack the company-held [Pune](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pune), were unexpectedly met by an 800-strong Company force that was on its way to reinforce the British troops in Pune. The Peshwa dispatched around 2,000 soldiers to attack the force which sought entrenchment in Koregaon. Led by Captain Francis Staunton, the Company troops defended their position for nearly 12 hours, before the Peshwa's troops ultimately withdrew, fearing the imminent arrival of a larger British force.
    - The battle was part of the [Third Anglo Maratha war](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Anglo-Maratha_War), a series of battles that culminated in the defeat of the Peshwa rule and subsequent rule of the British East India Company in nearly all of Western, Central and Southern India.[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-2) There is a "victory pillar" ([obelisk](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obelisk)) in Koregaon commemorating the battle.[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-3)
    - When Elphinstone visited the battle field shortly after its completion, he found that the Company soldiers had completely lost their morale and were reluctant to believe the praises that were showered on them .[[20]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-20)
    - General Smith arrived in Koregaon on 3 January, but by this time, the Peshwa had already left the area.[[11]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-HTP_1825-11) A company force led by General Pritzler pursued Peshwa, who tried to escape to [Mysore](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysore_State). Meanwhile, General Smith captured [Satara](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satara_(city)), the capital of Pratap Singh. Smith intercepted Peshwa in a battle on 19 February 1818 at Ashtoon (or Ashta); Bapuji Gokhale was killed in this action. The Peshwa then fled to [Khandesh](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khandesh), while his [jagirdars](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jagirdar) accepted the Company's suzerainty. A dejected Peshwa then met with [John Malcolm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Malcolm) on 2 June 1818, and surrendered his royal claims in exchange for a pension and a residence in [Bithoor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bithoor). Trimbakji Dengle was captured near Nashik and imprisoned at the [Chunar Fort](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chunar_Fort).[[9]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-Peter_1837-9)
    - As a reward for their bravery in the Battle of Koregaon, the 2nd battalion of the 1st Regiment of the Bombay Native Infantry was made [Grenadiers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grenadier). Their regiment came to be known as [1st Grenadier Regiment of Bombay Native Infantry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/102nd_Prince_of_Wales%27s_Own_Grenadiers).[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-Gazetteer1885-1) The official report to the British Residents at Poona recalls the "heroic valour and enduring fortitude" of the soldiers, the "disciplined intrepidity" and "devoted courage and admirable consistency" of their actions.[[21]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-EPW-21)
    - Captain Staunton was appointed an honorary [aide-de-camp](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aide-de-camp) to the [Governor General of India](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Governor_General_of_India). The [Court of Directors](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_East_India_Company_directors) presented him with a sword and a sum of 500 [guineas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guinea_(British_coin)) (gold coins). Later in 1823, he became a Major, and was appointed a companion of the [Most Honourable Military Order of the Bath](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_Bath).[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-Gazetteer1885-1)
    - General [Thomas Hislop](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Thomas_Hislop,_1st_Baronet) called the battle "one of the most heroic and brilliant achievements ever recorded on the annals of the army".[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-Gazetteer1885-1) According to M.S. Naravane, "this gallant defense by a small number of Company's troops against an overwhelming Maratha force is rightly considered as one of the most glorious example of valour and fortitude in the annals of the Company's forces."[[22]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-Naravane-22)
    - General Smith, in his official report of this battle, wrote, “The action at Koregaum was one of the most brilliant affairs achieved by any army in which European and Native soldiers displayed the most noble devotion and most romantic bravery under pressure of hunger and thirst almost beyond human endurance. [[23]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-23)
    - Neither side achieved a decisive victory in the battle.[[24]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-FOOTNOTEShraddha_Kumbhojkar201540-24)  Shortly after the battle, [Mountstuart Elphinstone](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mountstuart_Elphinstone)  described it as a "small victory" for the Peshwa.[[25]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-25)  Nevertheless, the East India Company government praised the bravery of its troops, who could not be overpowered despite being outnumbered.[[24]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-FOOTNOTEShraddha_Kumbhojkar201540-24)
    - Notwithstanding this, the battle being one of the last ones to be fought in the [Third Anglo-Maratha War](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Anglo-Maratha_War), is since recognised as a Company victory after the war ended with Peshwa's defeat.[[24]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Koregaon#cite_note-FOOTNOTEShraddha_Kumbhojkar201540-24)
